Problem

Tony is a recent graduate who wants to pursue a masters degree but doesnt have enough money. He decides to borrow $300,000 from Direct Plus with a 7.08% annual interest rate, compounded monthly. After graduation, Tony begins repaying the loan with a starting salary of $100,000 per year, increasing by 4% each year. With living expenses averaging $32,000 per year, Tony has $68,000 per year left to repay the loan, equating to $5,667 per month. Assuming a discount rate of 1.5% per year, Tony considers three repayment plans:

  1. Option 1 (Max repayment to clear debt quickly): Pay 30% of his post-living expense income monthly until the debt is cleared. Total payment: $519,440 over 239 months.

  2. Option 2 (Minimum repayment to manage risk): Pay 10% of his post-living expense income monthly for 25 years. The government forgives the remaining debt, but Tony pays 40% tax on the forgiven amount. Total payment: $527,666 over 25 years.

  3. Option 3 (Hybrid): Follow Option 1 for 102 months, then switch to Option 2 for the remaining 198 months. The government forgives the remaining debt, but Tony pays 40% tax on the forgiven amount. Total payment: $493,168 over 25 years.

Finally, Tony chooses Option 3 to balance cost and risk. But how does Tony calculate these payments, and how does he know 102 months is the optimal switch point?

First Option

A <- 1 + 0.0708/12
B <- 1.04^{1/12}
C <- 1.015^{1/12}
x_1 <- c(0:239)
y <- round(300000*A^x_1 - 1700*(A^x_1 - B^x_1)/(A - B), 2)
y_1 <- round(1700/C*((B/C)^x_1-1)/((B/C)-1),2)
monthly_repayment <- round(1700*B^{x_1-1},2)
monthly_repayment[1]=0
monthly_repayment[240]=0
discounted_monthly_repayment <- round(1700/C*(B/C)^{x_1-1},2)
discounted_monthly_repayment[1]=0
discounted_monthly_repayment[240]=0
y[240]=0
y_1[240] <- round(y_1[239] + A*y[239],2)

first_option_df <- data.frame(x_1, y, monthly_repayment, discounted_monthly_repayment, y_1)
names(first_option_df) <- c("Month", "Loan remaining", "Monthly repayment", "Discounted monthly repayment","Total paid money")
first_option_df %>% datatable()

Loans after months

plot(x_1, y[!y < 0], main = "First Option", col.main="orange", xlab="Months", ylab="Loans after months", type = "l", col ="red")

Third Option: A hybrid between First and Second Option

Find critical horizon

X_3 <- c(0:210)
Y_3 <- 0.4/C^{300}*(300000*A^{300} - 1700*(A^{X_3}-B^{X_3})*A^{300 - X_3}/(A-B) - 1700 * B^{X_3}* (A^{300 - X_3} - B^{300 - X_3})/(3*A-3*B))
Y_4 <- 1700*((B/C)^{X_3} - 1)/(B - C) + 1700*(B/C)^{X_3}*((B/C)^{300-X_3} - 1)/(3*B - 3*C)
Y_5 <- Y_3 + Y_4

Applying SAVE PLAN

m <- c(0:239)
T_1 <- 0.4/C^{300}*(300000 - 1300*(B^m - 1)/(B - 1) - 1300/3*B^m*(B^{300 - m} - 1)/(B - 1))
T_2 <- 1300/C*((B/C)^m - 1)/(B/C - 1)
T_3 <- 1300*(B/C)^m/(3*C)*((B/C)^{300-m} - 1)/(B/C - 1)
SAVE <- T_1 + T_2 + T_3
